For the following feature file, makeotf v2.0.90 (Nov 19 2015) generates a GDEF table with surprising GlyphClassDef entries:
```
languagesystem DFLT dflt;

@A_MARKS = [acute grave macron];
@B_MARKS = [ogonek];
markClass [caron cedilla] <anchor 350 0> @C_MARKS;

lookup A {
    lookupflag MarkAttachmentType @A_MARKS;
    pos A 1;
} A;

lookup B {
    lookupflag MarkAttachmentType @B_MARKS;
    pos B 1;
} B;

lookup C {
    lookupflag MarkAttachmentType @C_MARKS;
    pos C 1;
} C;

lookup D {
    lookupflag RightToLeft IgnoreBaseGlyphs MarkAttachmentType @C_MARKS;
    pos D 1;
} D;

lookup E {
    lookupflag RightToLeft;
    pos E 1;
} E;

lookup F {
    lookupflag IgnoreBaseGlyphs;
    pos F 1;
} F;

lookup G {
    lookupflag IgnoreLigatures;
    pos G 1;
} G;

lookup H {
    lookupflag IgnoreLigatures;
    pos H 1;
} H;

lookup I {
    lookupflag 6;
    pos I 1;
} I;

feature test {
    lookup A;
    lookup B;
    lookup C;
    lookup D;
    lookup E;
    lookup F;
    lookup G;
    lookup H;
    lookup I;
} test;
```

Observed output:
```
  <GDEF>
    <Version value="1.0"/>
    <GlyphClassDef>
      <ClassDef glyph="caron" class="3"/>
      <ClassDef glyph="cedilla" class="3"/>
      <ClassDef glyph="hungarumlaut" class="0"/>
      <ClassDef glyph="ogonek" class="0"/>
    </GlyphClassDef>
    <MarkAttachClassDef>
      <ClassDef glyph="acute" class="1"/>
      <ClassDef glyph="caron" class="3"/>
      <ClassDef glyph="cedilla" class="3"/>
      <ClassDef glyph="grave" class="1"/>
      <ClassDef glyph="macron" class="1"/>
      <ClassDef glyph="ogonek" class="2"/>
    </MarkAttachClassDef>
  </GDEF>
```

Expected:

* The produced GDEF table should not have a GlyphClassDef entry for `hungarumlaut`. This glyph was not even mentioned in the input feature file.

* The produced GDEF table should not contain any GlyphClassDef entries with class 0. According to the [GDEF specification](https://www.microsoft.com/typography/otspec/gdef.htm), “[t]he font developer does not have to classify every glyph in the font, but any glyph not assigned a class value falls into Class zero (0).” Thus, since the default is zero, there is no need to emit entries with class 0.

Commands to reproduce on MacOS X 10.11.1:
```
$ md5 Skia.ttf 
MD5 (Skia.ttf) = 13711112e6da2dda19bdeee76c52c91d
$ makeotf -f Skia.ttf -ff lookupflag.fea -o out.ttf ; ttx  -t GDEF out.ttf ; cat out.ttx
```

